th: 1024px) 1280px, (min-width: 640px) 768px, calc(100vw/3)" loading="lazy" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-uojGG kTBJzQ pf-16_"/></div></div></div><div class="sc-kfPuZi ihOOoE pf-17_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-jHkVzv dZEEUA pf-18_"><p class="sc-gIDmLj eMdhGW pf-19_" tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">It's back to school season! In honor of school starting back, let's go back to the ABC's of skincare! We'll dive into the foundation of a good skincare routine by re-learning the basics: (A) Vitamin A, (B) Broad Spectrum Sunscreen, and (C) Vitamin C. These three key components can help you achieve radiant, youthful skin - all year long!</p><h3 tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-brSvTw kXcmVH pf-21_">A is for Vitamin A</h3><p class="sc-gIDmLj eMdhGW pf-23_" tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Retinol, retinoid, retin-A, tretinoin - you've heard of them as the holy grail of anti-aging, but are probably confused as to what the ditterence is between them (trust me, you're not alone!). "Retinoid" is an umbrella term - it refers to anything in the Vitamin A family. Retinoids come in many ditferent forms and strengths. To make things simple, I created this retinoid hierarchy graphic (below) showing which retinoids are stronger/weaker than others. The lower the strength, the less collagen is stimulated - the higher the strength, the more collagen is stimulated. And we always want MORE collagen because that means LESS aging and wrinkles!</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-kfPuZi ihOOoE pf-25_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-jHkVzv dZEEUA pf-26_"><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0217/2305/4144/files/Screenshot_2023-08-23_at_11.17.03_AM_500x.png?v=1692803833" srcSe